00:17.685 --> 00:21.856
Many claim a supplement has freed them
from a life of prescription pain pills,

00:21.897 --> 00:24.566
while others say it is a dangerous
unregulated substance.

00:24.608 --> 00:26.193
It's called kratom.

00:26.234 --> 00:28.153
What we're hoping to have today
is a meaningful discussion,

00:28.195 --> 00:30.906
and we have, joining us, a
panel of kratom proponents,

00:30.948 --> 00:33.826
documentary filmmaker, Chris Bell...

00:33.868 --> 00:36.077
[Chris Bell] <i> Why does
this always happen to me?</i>

00:36.119 --> 00:38.580
<i>It seems like I always end up in the middle.</i>

00:38.622 --> 00:41.082
<i>In my first film,</i> Bigger Stronger Faster,

00:41.124 --> 00:45.044
<i>my brothers were both using steroids,
and I wasn't.</i>

00:45.086 --> 00:48.883
<i>I was stuck in the middle of following
the rules, or being the best.</i>

00:48.924 --> 00:50.885
<i>In my second film,</i> Trophy Kids,

00:50.926 --> 00:52.845
<i>I ended up in the middle of anxious parents</i>

00:52.887 --> 00:55.597
<i>living vicariously through their children's
sports dreams.</i>

00:55.639 --> 00:57.516
[man] Pull your head out of your ass, dude,
seriously.

00:57.558 --> 01:01.603
Can you be any stupider? How dumb!

01:01.645 --> 01:04.397
[Chris] <i> In Prescription Thugs,</i>
I exposed Big Pharma...

01:04.438 --> 01:07.234
- [Chris] How many pills a day were you doing?
- Ninety.

01:07.275 --> 01:10.529
[Chris] <i> ...as well as my own addiction</i>
<i>to opioid painkillers.</i>

01:10.571 --> 01:14.408
<i>See, the thing is, before I was a filmmaker,
I was a powerlifter</i>

01:14.449 --> 01:16.410
<i>and I wasn't half bad.</i>

01:16.451 --> 01:18.286
<i>Lifting gave me purpose.</i>

01:18.328 --> 01:19.830
<i>I was a shy, chubby kid.</i>

01:19.872 --> 01:21.415
<i>But when I started breaking records,</i>

01:21.456 --> 01:23.834
<i>and lifting more than my older brother
Mad Dog,</i>

01:23.876 --> 01:26.962
<i>people began to notice, and it felt good.</i>

01:27.004 --> 01:29.548
<i>I even got my little brother Smelly involved.</i>

01:29.590 --> 01:32.300
<i>At one point, we had so many trophies
from lifting,</i>

01:32.342 --> 01:34.595
<i>that we'd just throw them in the garbage.</i>

01:34.636 --> 01:37.180
<i>I no longer wanted to be like my heroes.</i>

01:37.222 --> 01:40.392
<i>I just wanted to be the
strongest man in the world.</i>

01:40.434 --> 01:44.521
<i>But what I didn't realize is, all
that wear and tear on the human body</i>

01:44.563 --> 01:46.440
<i>comes with a price.</i>

01:46.481 --> 01:48.275
<i>And, for me, that price was...</i>

01:48.316 --> 01:49.651
Pain.

01:49.693 --> 01:51.946
[Chris] <i> Shortly after</i> Bigger Stronger Faster,

01:51.987 --> 01:54.364
<i>I had both of my hips completely replaced</i>

01:54.406 --> 01:56.199
<i>due to a genetic condition.</i>

01:56.241 --> 02:01.038
<i>My dad had hip surgery at 17.
So, it runs in the family.</i>

02:01.080 --> 02:05.208
<i>This is a double hip replacement surgery.
And I'm only 35 years old.</i>

02:05.250 --> 02:09.088
<i>Sounds scary, right? Well, not for me.</i>

02:09.128 --> 02:11.423
<i>They told me I was going to
be walking the same day.</i>

02:11.465 --> 02:14.551
<i>This is what they mean
by walking the same day.</i>

02:14.593 --> 02:17.930
<i>I'm high on painkillers. So,
all I can picture is myself</i>

02:17.972 --> 02:21.850
<i>all jacked and tan, in a</i> Rocky <i> montage,
making a comeback.</i>

02:24.061 --> 02:27.856
<i>The more it hurt, the more pills I took.</i>

02:27.898 --> 02:31.610
<i>But when I was about to turn that corner
and run up the stairs,</i>

02:31.652 --> 02:37.532
<i>my brother Mad Dog died in a sober
living facility, at 37 years old.</i>

02:37.574 --> 02:41.954
<i>After seeing my brother die, and knowing
that drugs were at the core of it,</i>

02:41.996 --> 02:44.498
<i>you would think I would stop taking pills.</i>

02:44.539 --> 02:48.585
<i>But at that point, it was too late.
I was addicted.</i>

02:48.627 --> 02:52.380
<i>My life was going off the rails,
but I wasn't the only one.</i>

02:52.422 --> 02:56.259
<i>It seemed like our whole country
was popping pills.</i>

02:56.301 --> 03:01.598
<i>American account for the use of
approximately 99% of one specific opioid,</i>

03:01.640 --> 03:03.976
<i>a powerful painkiller called hydrocodone.</i>

03:04.018 --> 03:08.522
Every day, 91 Americans die
from an overdose of opioids,

03:08.563 --> 03:11.108
<i>which include prescription
painkillers and heroin.</i>

03:11.150 --> 03:14.528
We know that four out of five new heroin users

03:14.569 --> 03:16.113
started on prescription pills.

03:16.155 --> 03:20.826
We saw more people die of drug overdoses

03:20.868 --> 03:23.078
than die of car accidents.

03:23.120 --> 03:24.872
[news anchor] <i> In and around
Huntington, West Virginia,</i>

03:24.913 --> 03:28.709
28 overdoses occurred in one five-hour span.

03:28.750 --> 03:33.338
[Chris] <i> The point that everyone is missing
is that we don't have an opioid epidemic,</i>

03:33.380 --> 03:37.134
<i>we have a pain epidemic, and we're
just treating the wrong thing.</i>

03:37.176 --> 03:42.389
You've been doing a documentary about
all the different components

03:42.430 --> 03:44.808
of addiction, of selling these pills,

03:44.850 --> 03:46.977
and yet, you still got sucked into their web.

03:47.019 --> 03:48.979
Yeah, exactly, that's how powerful it is.

03:49.021 --> 03:53.108
But you are about as educated
about it as a person can be.

03:53.150 --> 03:55.110
I think now I am.

03:55.152 --> 03:57.946
[Chris] <i> During the making of</i> Prescription
Thugs, <i>the film was delayed,</i>

03:57.988 --> 03:59.698
<i>and the funding got pulled,</i>

03:59.740 --> 04:01.700
<i>and I didn't know how to handle it.</i>

04:01.742 --> 04:05.620
<i>I relapsed and ended up back on pills.</i>

04:05.662 --> 04:09.249
<i>They say you haven't made it in Hollywood
until you've been to rehab.</i>

04:09.290 --> 04:13.003
<i>So, I went out to Malibu
to face my demons head on.</i>

04:13.045 --> 04:17.048
<i>But after 90 days of rehab, and doing
everything that was asked of me,</i>

04:17.091 --> 04:20.802
<i>there was one big glaring problem
that rehab couldn't fix:</i>

04:22.221 --> 04:24.181
<i>I was still in pain.</i>

04:36.777 --> 04:40.114
<i>I had kicked my addiction and was
back on the straight and narrow.</i>

04:40.155 --> 04:43.450
<i>I began searching for alternatives
to relieve my pain.</i>

04:46.494 --> 04:48.956
So, after I got done with the opioids,

04:48.997 --> 04:50.791
I was on Dr. Drew's show,

04:50.832 --> 04:53.334
and he said, "Well, you should try Advil
and Tylenol in combination."

04:53.376 --> 04:55.629
"That's going to be better than an opioid
for your chronic pain."

04:55.670 --> 04:57.589
So, I said, "Okay." I start trying that.

04:57.631 --> 05:00.592
Then I get a phone call from my friend
who lives in England,

05:00.634 --> 05:02.343
who tells me he just had a kidney transplant

05:02.385 --> 05:04.304
because of all the NSAIDs he was taking.

05:04.345 --> 05:07.307
[Chris] <i>NSAIDs are non-steroidal</i>
<i>anti-inflammatories.</i>

05:07.348 --> 05:12.146
<i>Things like the painkillers found
in Advil, Aleve, and aspirin.</i>

05:12.187 --> 05:14.940
<i>So, what's the answer? Am I supposed to just
live with the pain?</i>

05:17.025 --> 05:19.486
<i>Then I get a call from a familiar voice.</i>

05:19.527 --> 05:22.781
It's good to see you. I missed you, man.
I haven't seen you in so long.

05:22.823 --> 05:24.950
- We haven't even talked in a while.
- What's up?

05:24.992 --> 05:27.828
[Chris] <i> My friend Horshu said he'd discovered</i>
<i>the holy grail,</i>

05:27.869 --> 05:31.706
<i>a natural painkiller that won't kill you,
called kratom.</i>

05:31.748 --> 05:35.543
- [Chris] When did you start taking it?
- About nine months ago. Yeah.

05:35.585 --> 05:37.671
- And how do you feel?
- I feel great.

05:37.712 --> 05:39.589
Yeah, so we talked in <i> Prescription Thugs,</i>

05:39.631 --> 05:43.093
you had "a massive, massive, massive stroke,"
in the words of your doctor.

05:43.135 --> 05:45.846
- Does it help with that?
- It helped me immensely.

05:45.887 --> 05:48.307
- How do you handle pain?
- I take kratom.

05:48.347 --> 05:51.392
- How did you handle it before?
- Look, man, I would stand up,

05:51.434 --> 05:53.728
I'd stand up, I'd walk like this.
You remember.

05:53.770 --> 05:55.480
I'd be walking like this.

05:55.522 --> 05:58.525
You know what I mean? Hunched
over for 20 minutes,

05:58.566 --> 06:01.111
- you know what I mean? Walking slow.
- Yes, slowly...

06:01.153 --> 06:04.823
Now I just stand up... Stand up, walk around.

06:04.865 --> 06:06.616
You know, when that study came out,

06:06.658 --> 06:08.618
<i>- I was like, "65 wrestlers under the age of 50..."</i>
- [Wiese] <i> Yeah.</i>

06:08.660 --> 06:13.081
- ..."have died. And they blame steroids all the time, right?"
- Yeah. [scoffs]

06:13.123 --> 06:18.086
It's not steroids. It's the wrong combination
of drugs.

06:18.128 --> 06:23.258
It's probably alcohol with Vicodin,
with cocaine, you know what I mean?

06:23.300 --> 06:26.594
[Kurt Angle] <i> I knew as long as I
stuffed myself with painkillers,</i>

06:26.636 --> 06:29.388
I couldn't feel it, and I
couldn't feel the pain.

06:29.430 --> 06:32.351
And I would go as long as I could
until my body couldn't go anymore.

06:32.391 --> 06:36.230
Yeah, Vicodin and vodka
were my closest friends.

06:36.271 --> 06:37.856
- [Reporter] Wow.
- And my closest enemies.

06:37.898 --> 06:41.400
Once I had the stroke, I refused to go back
to pain pills.

06:41.442 --> 06:42.861
You know, before I had the stroke,

06:42.903 --> 06:46.073
I was doing about 90 pain
pills a day for seven years.

06:46.114 --> 06:48.742
And then when I had the
stroke, when I recovered,

06:48.783 --> 06:52.329
I refused to go back to pain pills.
And I found kratom.

06:54.289 --> 06:57.667
[Chris] <i> Horshu pointed us to Vegas to meet</i>
<i>his friend Kelly,</i>

06:57.709 --> 07:00.461
<i>who's been selling kratom since 2010.</i>

07:00.503 --> 07:03.631
<i>He owns one of the top kratom companies</i>
<i>in the country.</i> I used to be into boats

07:03.673 --> 07:06.801
and boatracing, and so forth,
and I was in an accident

07:06.843 --> 07:08.387
where, you know, I broke my orbital,

07:08.427 --> 07:10.513
and broke the right side of
my face in a boat crash.

07:10.555 --> 07:14.059
When I went to the doctor, especially for
the orbital, there is nothing they can do.

07:14.101 --> 07:16.144
So, they give me pain medication.
They give me Percocets.

07:16.186 --> 07:20.523
And he gave me, I want to say 60 pills,
with three refills.

07:21.942 --> 07:24.319
- Worst off, I'd need it for...
- Yeah, a week.

07:24.361 --> 07:25.404
Yeah, a week maybe.

07:25.445 --> 07:27.447
Maybe four or five days, maybe.

07:27.488 --> 07:29.157
Like everybody else, I
started taking the Percs,

07:29.199 --> 07:30.867
and they kinda become a habit for me.

07:30.909 --> 07:33.036
Then you start thinking about, "Well, shit,"

07:33.078 --> 07:35.289
"my day might not function quite as well"

07:35.330 --> 07:37.291
"if I don't take this, I better take it."

07:37.332 --> 07:41.420
It led to the point where now when I
wanted to stop, I was going to get sick.

07:41.461 --> 07:44.923
Somebody had introduced me to kratom. I
was involved in the head shop industry.

07:44.965 --> 07:46.758
<i>I owned a couple of smoke shops at the time.</i>

07:46.800 --> 07:48.802
And introduced to kratom,

07:48.843 --> 07:51.679
and it was a real easy transition
out of the Percocets.

07:51.721 --> 07:55.350
What's so special about this stuff?
Why should we care about kratom?

07:55.392 --> 07:58.895
[Dunn] <i> You know, for one, because it's
been so helpful to so many people.</i>

07:58.937 --> 08:01.606
<i>We know that it's been a medicinal plant
for hundreds of years.</i>

08:01.648 --> 08:04.859
<i>There were tribes in Indonesia that used
to build their village</i>

08:04.901 --> 08:06.153
<i>around a series of kratom trees,</i>

08:06.194 --> 08:08.947
<i>because it was central to their way of life.</i>

08:08.989 --> 08:11.908
[Chris] <i> So, if people have been using this</i>
<i>for hundreds of years,</i>

08:11.950 --> 08:13.743
<i>Why have I never heard of it?</i>

08:13.785 --> 08:17.122
<i>Dr. Darshan Singh has been studying
the traditional uses of kratom</i>

08:17.164 --> 08:20.292
<i>in his homeland of Malaysia
for over ten years.</i>

08:20.334 --> 08:24.629
I've been spending a lot of time
on kratom research in Malaysia,

08:24.671 --> 08:27.799
and in Malaysia I'm known as Dr. kratom,
okay?

08:27.841 --> 08:31.678
So, I'd been going in, trying to understand
why people use kratom.

08:31.719 --> 08:34.306
<i>If I were to make my own kratom tea
for personal consumption,</i>

08:34.347 --> 08:38.309
<i>I would just have to go behind my house and
just pluck maybe like about 20 leaves,</i>

08:38.352 --> 08:42.272
just brew it, and I would just switch off
the fire,

08:42.313 --> 08:47.277
and then allow it to cool down, and
then just consume it the whole day.

08:47.319 --> 08:50.238
So, you guys don't have an
opioid crisis like we have...

08:50.280 --> 08:52.366
Oh, we have opioid addiction problem.

08:52.407 --> 08:56.286
People are using kratom to
self-treat opioid abuse,

08:56.328 --> 08:58.746
alcohol abuse, and crystal meth abuse.

08:58.788 --> 09:01.875
You can actually use kratom
to treat chronic pain.

09:01.916 --> 09:04.336
<i>And you can also use it to
treat opioid addiction,</i>

09:04.378 --> 09:07.047
<i>because opioid addiction is
also associated with pain.</i>

09:07.088 --> 09:09.841
In traditional settings,
those who are using kratom,

09:09.883 --> 09:15.305
they are not labeled or stereotyped
as drug addicts or drug users.

09:15.347 --> 09:17.682
They do not engage in criminal behavior.

09:17.724 --> 09:21.561
<i>If you were to compare heroin or
morphine users on the street,</i>

09:21.602 --> 09:23.730
<i>they do engage in risky behaviors,</i>

09:23.771 --> 09:27.234
they do commit crime, because they have
to support their addictive behaviors.

09:27.275 --> 09:29.110
While kratom users, in traditional settings,

09:29.152 --> 09:30.737
they use kratom for medicinal purpose.

09:30.778 --> 09:33.614
And people living in Southeast Asia,

09:33.656 --> 09:35.242
like from where I'm coming, Malaysia,

09:35.283 --> 09:38.870
people have been using kratom
for over 200 years, okay?

09:38.912 --> 09:41.998
And you need to make sure that you have

09:42.040 --> 09:47.045
genuine distributors of
kratom in the United States.

09:47.087 --> 09:51.508
[Chris] <i> If kratom is so great, then why
haven't I seen it on store shelves?</i>

09:51.550 --> 09:55.345
<i>Probably 'cause you can't get it
at your local pharmacy or GNC.</i>

09:55.387 --> 09:58.515
<i>For now, you have to venture
into your local smoke shop.</i>

09:58.557 --> 10:01.059
<i>And that's not usually
where I get my medicine.</i>

10:01.101 --> 10:06.106
So, this is more what I would picture,
like, a supplement to look like.

10:06.147 --> 10:07.107
Yeah.

10:08.275 --> 10:09.526
[speaks indistinctly]

10:09.568 --> 10:10.527
Yeah.

10:12.779 --> 10:14.489
Happy kratom.

10:14.531 --> 10:18.659
I was in the army for six years, and I have
friends with PTSD, who...

10:18.701 --> 10:20.370
They give them this drug and that drug,

10:20.412 --> 10:23.206
and they all have bad side effects,
and they get hooked on them.

10:23.248 --> 10:25.459
But they can use this, not get hooked on it,

10:25.500 --> 10:27.586
and not have all the bad effects.

10:27.627 --> 10:29.754
I'm not going to say it's
going to cure it 100%.

10:29.796 --> 10:33.633
But it helps them live day-to-day
without having an outburst,

10:33.674 --> 10:36.219
or having a flashback.

10:36.261 --> 10:39.514
- It just lets them have a normal life.
- [Chris] Yeah.

10:39.556 --> 10:42.976
[Rezvani] I work seven days a week,
and my feet, trust me, they kill me.

10:43.017 --> 10:46.313
- [chuckles]
- And then I take it, and after, like, half an hour,

10:46.354 --> 10:50.775
it's a different feeling. I
don't feel that pain anymore.

10:50.817 --> 10:53.736
And it makes it easier for
me to go on with my day.

10:53.778 --> 10:55.738
[Chris] <i> Okay, so people take kratom</i>

10:55.780 --> 10:57.698
<i>because they want to self-medicate.</i>

10:57.740 --> 11:02.162
<i>But before I try it, I wanted to
talk to an expert on this stuff.</i>

11:02.203 --> 11:04.038
<i>So, I found Dr. Schoenwetter.</i>

11:04.080 --> 11:07.375
<i>He has a lot of patients come to him
to ween off of opiates.</i>

11:07.417 --> 11:09.794
<i>And often times, he recommends kratom.</i>

11:09.836 --> 11:13.465
<i>He's also been tracking the progress
of over 100 of his patients</i>

11:13.507 --> 11:15.008
<i>that are taking the plant.</i>

11:15.049 --> 11:19.053
There are so many compounds within the plant,

11:19.095 --> 11:21.556
that the plant itself is a virtual pharmacy.

11:21.598 --> 11:25.519
The beauty of this, of course,
is that you don't need me

11:25.560 --> 11:27.228
to write it on a piece of paper.

11:27.270 --> 11:29.063
You can just get it yourself.

11:29.105 --> 11:32.275
So, it's a great backup tool if you
need something with a little more

11:32.317 --> 11:34.068
oomph than leaf.

11:34.110 --> 11:38.072
<i>There's a thing called affinity,
and a thing called activity.</i>

11:38.114 --> 11:41.784
<i>Affinity is how much substance
will stick to a receptor.</i>

11:43.995 --> 11:47.790
<i>So, if you can imagine having superglue
on your finger,</i>

11:47.832 --> 11:51.044
<i>- and touching a piano key...</i>
- [plays note]

11:51.085 --> 11:53.838
<i>...you've got a very high degree of affinity.</i>

11:53.880 --> 11:57.217
<i>But activity...</i> [laughs] <i>Even
though you're stuck to the key,</i>

11:57.258 --> 12:01.304
<i>- you may not be able to press the key very loud.</i>
- [plays note]

12:01.346 --> 12:05.559
<i>Kratom seems to have a high affinity</i>

12:05.600 --> 12:08.936
<i>for some of the opioid receptors,
but it has a ceiling</i>

12:08.978 --> 12:12.190
<i>and so, it has a limited activity.</i>
[chuckles]

12:12.232 --> 12:15.902
<i>It's not dangerous. But heroin,
or a strong opiate,</i>

12:15.943 --> 12:18.029
<i>can push the key to make it really loud.</i>

12:18.071 --> 12:20.990
[loud discordant notes]

12:22.783 --> 12:26.829
<i>Whereas buprenorphine and kratom aren't able
to make it as loud.</i>

12:26.871 --> 12:30.667
<i>They're stuck to the key, but they
can't make it play as loud.</i> [chuckles]

12:31.626 --> 12:33.211
I'm taking it today

12:33.253 --> 12:35.796
because I've had problems with arthritis
and a knee effusion.

12:35.838 --> 12:38.675
So, I'm able now to get off the walker,

12:38.717 --> 12:42.136
and get off the offloader knee brace,
and I'm back to myself.

12:42.178 --> 12:45.223
So, tell me how you came across kratom.

12:45.265 --> 12:48.059
I got introduced to it as the guy

12:48.101 --> 12:49.894
who was putting gas in the car.

12:49.936 --> 12:51.938
<i>My wife had a migraine headache.</i>

12:51.979 --> 12:55.358
<i>She said, "Well, I'll go dig up
something here at the station."</i>

12:55.400 --> 12:57.776
<i>At that time, a lady of the evening
was stepping in.</i>

12:57.818 --> 13:00.321
<i>And reached behind by the cigarettes,</i>

13:00.363 --> 13:03.658
<i>and alcohol, and pulled out a packet
of kratom.</i>

13:03.700 --> 13:06.494
<i>My wife immediately said, "What's that?"</i>

13:06.536 --> 13:09.956
<i>The kind lady said, "It makes a lot
of the aches and pains just go away."</i>

13:09.997 --> 13:11.583
<i>Karen says, "I'll take one."</i>

13:11.625 --> 13:13.834
Got in the car and said, "Phil,
what do you know about this?"

13:13.876 --> 13:18.339
I know nothing. Absolutely nothing.

13:18.381 --> 13:23.511
I drove on. We headed south, and
about 65 miles later, she said,

13:23.553 --> 13:25.597
"Phil, the headache's gone."

13:25.639 --> 13:28.558
I said, "Really?" I said, "Do you feel drowsy,
