01:06:19.559 --> 01:06:23.313
Whenever we send product out for testing,
like all of this product sitting here,

01:06:23.354 --> 01:06:26.733
none of this can be used yet, because
we don't have test results back yet.

01:06:26.775 --> 01:06:28.067
So every batch, you have to test it?

01:06:28.109 --> 01:06:29.945
- [Dunn] Have to, no, but we do.
- Yeah.

01:06:29.986 --> 01:06:31.613
<i>We actually test it three times.</i>

01:06:31.655 --> 01:06:33.865
<i>The FDA put out this import alert that says,</i>

01:06:33.907 --> 01:06:37.034
we're not allowed to import this because
they don't feel it's safe.

01:06:37.076 --> 01:06:39.496
- But they never tested it, so I mean...
- Sure.

01:06:39.537 --> 01:06:42.206
They're basing their opinion without tests.

01:06:42.248 --> 01:06:43.750
So many people talk shit about the FDA,

01:06:43.792 --> 01:06:46.127
- but we really need to support the FDA...
- Yes, we do.

01:06:46.169 --> 01:06:48.379
...because once everybody gets onboard,

01:06:48.421 --> 01:06:52.008
and you know, when the FDA says,
"Okay, this is a full supplement,"

01:06:52.049 --> 01:06:54.594
now, we go back to pharmaceutical co-packers.

01:06:54.636 --> 01:06:57.263
- Yes.
- So, now everything's done in a clinical environment.

01:06:57.305 --> 01:07:00.099
We don't have to build each
individual little segment.

01:07:00.141 --> 01:07:03.353
I'm surprised there hasn't been a politician,
and maybe we need to find one,

01:07:03.394 --> 01:07:05.689
that gets behind this.

01:07:05.730 --> 01:07:08.775
142 Americans are dying every day

01:07:08.817 --> 01:07:10.735
of drug overdose, every day.

01:07:10.777 --> 01:07:15.949
Which means we have a 9/11-scale loss
every three weeks in America.

01:07:15.991 --> 01:07:17.701
<i>So, the first recommendation
we say to the president is,</i>

01:07:17.742 --> 01:07:19.577
<i>you must declare national emergency.</i>

01:07:19.619 --> 01:07:21.955
This problem, Jake, is not happening,

01:07:21.997 --> 01:07:23.790
it's not starting on our street corners.

01:07:23.832 --> 01:07:26.626
It's starting in our doctors'
offices and hospitals.

01:07:26.668 --> 01:07:29.587
[Chris] <i> Another politician trying to fix this</i>
<i>opioid crisis</i>

01:07:29.629 --> 01:07:31.464
<i>is Congressman Mark Pocan.</i>

01:07:31.506 --> 01:07:34.175
<i>But kratom's illegal in
his state of Wisconsin,</i>

01:07:34.217 --> 01:07:36.135
<i>and he wants to see that changed.</i>

01:07:36.177 --> 01:07:38.179
<i>So, he and his colleague, Matt Salmon,</i>

01:07:38.221 --> 01:07:40.348
<i>wrote a bipartisan letter to Congress</i>

01:07:40.390 --> 01:07:42.392
<i>begging them to keep kratom legal.</i>

01:07:42.433 --> 01:07:44.978
<i>And they got 50 other congressmen to sign it,</i>

01:07:45.020 --> 01:07:48.105
<i>which, by today's standards, is huge.</i>

01:07:48.147 --> 01:07:50.901
This is one where I think the other people
are way ahead of

01:07:50.942 --> 01:07:53.110
elected officials, on issues like this.

01:07:53.152 --> 01:07:54.863
They don't see it as an issue.

01:07:54.905 --> 01:07:56.907
<i>And when kratom came up again,</i>

01:07:56.948 --> 01:07:59.826
<i>it's something that's been legal in virtually
every state in the country.</i>

01:07:59.868 --> 01:08:02.037
We haven't had problems with it,

01:08:02.078 --> 01:08:04.372
and then, all of a sudden,
to see it go to Schedule I

01:08:04.414 --> 01:08:06.457
just raised that red flag,
that we thought we needed

01:08:06.499 --> 01:08:09.210
to at least try to find a
way to put brakes on it.

01:08:09.252 --> 01:08:11.755
And I think the important part is
we did it in a bipartisan way,

01:08:11.796 --> 01:08:13.172
'cause, you know, so often

01:08:13.214 --> 01:08:14.841
things are either done from
the Left or the Right.

01:08:14.883 --> 01:08:16.426
Sometimes you just gotta do it

01:08:16.466 --> 01:08:18.761
right from where it needs to be addressed,
from both sides.

01:08:18.803 --> 01:08:22.432
And do you think that banning kratom could
actually hurt people?

01:08:22.473 --> 01:08:25.018
Absolutely. I mean, one... I mean, there are
a number of people

01:08:25.060 --> 01:08:26.978
that we talked to since doing that,

01:08:27.020 --> 01:08:29.188
who've shared stories like yours.

01:08:29.229 --> 01:08:31.858
That this is something that helps them,

01:08:31.899 --> 01:08:33.693
especially people who've
been addicted to opioids.

01:08:33.734 --> 01:08:37.863
To take that away would seem wrong,
especially if there's not

01:08:37.906 --> 01:08:40.283
hard evidence as a reason why, and so far,

01:08:40.323 --> 01:08:42.035
I haven't seen any hard evidence

01:08:42.077 --> 01:08:44.412
that makes sense why you could justify

01:08:44.453 --> 01:08:45.580
putting it on Schedule I.

01:08:45.622 --> 01:08:47.497
In fact, if anything, there's research,

01:08:47.540 --> 01:08:51.167
<i>including from universities that are looking
at the positive effects</i>

01:08:51.210 --> 01:08:53.004
<i>of something like kratom.</i>

01:08:53.046 --> 01:08:54.881
<i>Part of why we have the opioid problem
we have is that there is</i>

01:08:54.923 --> 01:08:56.883
<i>almost an over-prescription of opioids,</i>

01:08:56.925 --> 01:09:00.176
and then an overreaction, like we often do,
to stopping it.

01:09:00.219 --> 01:09:03.680
And then if people couldn't get now
what they got addicted to,

01:09:03.723 --> 01:09:05.475
they went to the street and got heroin.

01:09:05.515 --> 01:09:08.812
And I recently was visiting a hospital
in my district.

01:09:08.853 --> 01:09:11.272
<i>A doctor came late. He goes,
"I'm sorry, I had my daily</i>

01:09:11.314 --> 01:09:13.733
<i>heroin overdose to deal with. I just got done.</i>

01:09:13.774 --> 01:09:16.027
I was dealing with someone who came in."

01:09:16.069 --> 01:09:20.156
You know, we should be
shooting for every possible

01:09:20.197 --> 01:09:23.701
alternative way to make sure you can
get people off of opioids.

01:09:23.743 --> 01:09:26.578
And unfortunately, I don't
think we're doing that,

01:09:26.621 --> 01:09:28.247
if we look at things like kratom

01:09:28.288 --> 01:09:31.792
as Schedule I rather than,
potentially, a solution.

01:09:31.835 --> 01:09:34.587
[Chris] <i> Another potential solution</i>
<i>for this opioid crisis</i>

01:09:34.629 --> 01:09:36.296
<i>might be ibogaine.</i>

01:09:36.339 --> 01:09:38.549
<i>Iboga is a natural plant from Africa,</i>

01:09:38.591 --> 01:09:41.928
<i>that can turn 20-year heroin addictions around
in hours.</i>

01:09:41.970 --> 01:09:45.723
<i>The problem is it's a Schedule I drug
in the U.S.</i>

01:09:45.765 --> 01:09:49.144
<i>Dr. Deborah Mash is the world's
leading researcher on ibogaine,</i>

01:09:49.185 --> 01:09:51.354
<i>and she's fighting to make it legal.</i>

01:09:51.395 --> 01:09:53.564
<i>But I wonder what she thinks about kratom.</i>

01:09:53.606 --> 01:09:55.692
Well, as you may know,
I've spent my life's work

01:09:55.733 --> 01:09:57.944
working on a medication from Africa,

01:09:57.986 --> 01:10:01.156
another natural product called ibogaine.

01:10:01.197 --> 01:10:05.409
And ibogaine, which comes from
the region of Gabon in Cameroon,

01:10:05.451 --> 01:10:09.039
<i>another one of Mother Nature's alkaloids</i>

01:10:09.080 --> 01:10:13.209
<i>we know can be used to
successfully detox people</i>

01:10:13.250 --> 01:10:14.836
<i>off of opiates.</i>

01:10:14.878 --> 01:10:17.338
So, my worry is that,

01:10:17.380 --> 01:10:21.342
you know, we have people who
are not opiate abusers,

01:10:21.384 --> 01:10:23.887
who have never partied with opiates,

01:10:23.928 --> 01:10:27.182
who now get introduced to the euphoria

01:10:27.223 --> 01:10:30.393
<i>that kratom or mitragynine has.</i>

01:10:30.434 --> 01:10:35.272
I think there's pretty good evidence
that mitragynine is addictive.

01:10:35.314 --> 01:10:39.819
I think there's no doubt about the science
behind that.

01:10:39.861 --> 01:10:43.865
So, do we want another addicting opiate
on the planet?

01:10:43.907 --> 01:10:46.076
Does it need to be studied more?
Sure, it does.

01:10:46.117 --> 01:10:47.451
We need more research.

01:10:47.493 --> 01:10:50.955
We need better molecules to treat addiction.

01:10:50.997 --> 01:10:53.499
Is there a place for developing mitragynine

01:10:53.541 --> 01:10:55.210
for the treatment of addiction?

01:10:55.251 --> 01:10:56.669
I'm not sure.

01:10:56.711 --> 01:11:00.173
There are many different
ways that you can substitute

01:11:00.215 --> 01:11:05.011
an opiate to slide off of a heroin habit,

01:11:05.053 --> 01:11:07.097
and to not suffer from the withdrawals.

01:11:07.138 --> 01:11:08.723
And opiate withdrawals are terrible,

01:11:08.765 --> 01:11:11.517
so, we understand why patients

01:11:11.559 --> 01:11:14.938
<i>may wanna have access to kratom.</i>

01:11:14.979 --> 01:11:16.856
Okay? But I want it regulated.

01:11:16.898 --> 01:11:19.234
I don't want it being sold,

01:11:19.275 --> 01:11:20.944
and maybe I'm getting old,

01:11:20.985 --> 01:11:22.946
<i>I don't want it being sold in head shops.</i>

01:11:22.987 --> 01:11:25.698
I don't want young people playing with it.

01:11:25.740 --> 01:11:27.533
We don't know enough yet.

01:11:27.575 --> 01:11:30.870
And I understand that, historically,
a lot of people have used kratom.

01:11:30.912 --> 01:11:32.538
- [Chris] <i> Yeah.
- I get it.</i>

01:11:32.580 --> 01:11:35.458
But the bottom line that gives me pause
over and over again,

01:11:35.499 --> 01:11:38.586
is that we are faced now in the United States

01:11:38.628 --> 01:11:41.965
with a staggering epidemic

01:11:42.006 --> 01:11:44.592
- of opiate abuse and addiction.
- Yeah, huge.

01:11:44.634 --> 01:11:46.302
I don't wanna add to that.

01:11:46.343 --> 01:11:48.721
- I don't want more people introduced...
- Yeah.

01:11:48.763 --> 01:11:51.557
- ...to addicting opiates.
- But Pharma is actually putting out stronger opiates.

01:11:51.599 --> 01:11:53.184
Pharma is another story.

01:11:53.226 --> 01:11:54.435
- Okay?
- That's the problem, right?

01:11:54.477 --> 01:11:56.229
Well...

01:11:56.271 --> 01:11:58.898
- [chuckling]
- That's another, you know...

01:11:58.940 --> 01:12:00.608
- I can't fight that battle.
- Yeah.

01:12:00.650 --> 01:12:03.820
[Mash] <i> Do I think Pharma made mistakes?</i>
<i>Oh, yes, I do.</i>

01:12:03.861 --> 01:12:06.489
<i>Do I think they're responsible for some of
what we're seeing today?</i>

01:12:06.530 --> 01:12:08.449
<i>Yes, I do.</i>

01:12:08.491 --> 01:12:10.785
<i>But we also know there's more heroin
on the streets than ever before.</i>

01:12:10.827 --> 01:12:12.620
<i>- Right?</i>
- [Chris] <i> Yeah.</i>

01:12:12.662 --> 01:12:18.501
[Mash] <i> Post 9/11, Afghanistan and
the opium runs poisoned Americans.</i>

01:12:18.542 --> 01:12:20.211
<i>"Just bring those drugs in."</i>

01:12:20.253 --> 01:12:25.049
And what we need to do is we need to help
our brothers and sisters.

01:12:25.091 --> 01:12:28.303
We need to look at it with a humanistic eye

01:12:28.344 --> 01:12:32.098
to give people the opportunity to
kick the habit the best way we can.

01:12:32.140 --> 01:12:33.975
And we've gotta be bold.

01:12:34.017 --> 01:12:38.813
And maybe there's a place for kratom
under medical supervision,

01:12:38.855 --> 01:12:40.898
- or in treatment centers...
- Mm-hmm.

01:12:40.940 --> 01:12:44.694
...but, you know, without the money
to work that up,

01:12:45.569 --> 01:12:47.030
it's not going to happen.

01:12:47.071 --> 01:12:50.325
[Chris] <i> In this country, every
time we have an epidemic,</i>

01:12:50.366 --> 01:12:53.786
<i>we Stockton Slap it like the Diaz Brothers.</i>

01:12:53.828 --> 01:12:57.456
<i>We weren't gonna let measles, mumps,
